vectorData.altText: 28. Muscles on the medial aspect of the leg often have the word _______________ in their name.
That's right!  Muscles on the medial aspect of the leg are attached to the tibia, therefore they have the word ‘tibialis’ in their name.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

While the names of the muscles of the leg and foot are daunting at first glance, pretty quickly, you learn that the names are very descriptive and informative. For instance:
Muscles that act on the toes have the word digitorum     in their names. Ditto!
Muscles that act on the great toe have the word hallucis     in their names. Ditto!
Muscles that are flexors have the word flexor in their names. You get the idea!
Muscles that are extensors have the word extensor in their names.
Muscles on the medial (tibial) aspect of the leg have tibialis in their names.
Muscles on the lateral (fibular) aspect of the leg have fibularis      in their names.

Sometimes, two muscles might have the same attachments or the same action at the same joint. They are differentiated using descriptors, for instance:
If one is longer than the other, it has longus in its name and the other has brevis in its name.

The moral of this story, once again, is to use the names of the muscles to your advantage in learning their actions, locations, and, in some cases, their relative positions.
